Confirmed. Here's the answer:

## 1. File and symbols

`webclient/scripts/export_tasks.js`

- **`formatTaskRow(task)`** (lines 7–11) — assembles a single row.
- **`TaskExporter.exportTsv(stream)`** (lines 27–33) — the loop that writes each row to output.

## 2. Mechanism / where column order lives

Both row assembly *and* column order live in the same spot — there's no separate header/field-list constant. Line 10:

```js
return [task.id, status, title].join('\t');
```

The array literal `[task.id, status, title]` **is** the column order (id → status → title). `exportTsv` just calls `formatTaskRow(task)` per task and writes the result + `'\n'` to the stream (line 30) — it has no awareness of columns itself.

Notably, there's also no header row ever written — the file starts straight into data rows.

## To add a column

Change **only `formatTaskRow`** (`webclient/scripts/export_tasks.js:7-11`): compute the new field and append it to the array literal at the position you want, e.g.:

```js
function formatTaskRow(task) {
  const status = task.completedAt ? 'done' : 'open';
  const title = task.title.replace(/\t/g, ' ');
  const priority = task.priority ?? '';
  return [task.id, status, title, priority].join('\t');
}
```

Nothing in `exportTsv` or elsewhere needs to change, since it just forwards whatever `formatTaskRow` returns. (If you want a header row for spreadsheet import, that would need to be added separately in `exportTsv` — currently none exists.)

